In other words, the Nernst coefficient is a measure of transverse entropy flow caused by longitudinal particle flow.  As in the case of the Seebeck coefficient, this alternative definition provided by the application of Onsager reciprocity is strictly identical to the ratio of the transverse electric field to  the longitudinal thermal gradient invoked by the more common definition. This picture is particularly useful in setting a frame for the magnitude of the thermoelectric linked to fundamental constants and material dependent parameters.


